    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Claims Against Police</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert S Druce letter notes record amount of $40 million was spent by New York City in litigation against NYC Police Department in 1999 (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Claims Filed Against Officers Decline Sharply'' (front page, July 21):</p>
        <p>Instead of focusing on the number of complaints lodged against New York City police officers, one must look at the amount of money settled or litigated by the city from people wronged by the Police Department.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Claims Filed Against Officers Decline Sharply'' (front page, July 21):</p>
        <p>Instead of focusing on the number of complaints lodged against New York City police officers, one must look at the amount of money settled or litigated by the city from people wronged by the Police Department.</p>
        <p>Last year, it was $40 million -- a record amount.</p>
        <p>I suggest that rather than have the taxpayer foot the bill for police misconduct, it would be better to have the money taken out of the Police Department's budget. This would be a deterrent for future misconduct and a wake-up call to discipline bad officers.</p>
        <p>ROBERT S. DRUCE  New York, July 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
